tial People in Computer Gaming, \"honored for helping to bring back serious flight simulations that don't alienate beginners.\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100405233824/http://www.gamespot.com/features/15most/html/mi96_05.html GameSpot]</ref>\n \nWhen Origin changed its focus to online games, he moved around within Electronic Arts and was working on [[NASCAR]] games and a [[Harry Potter]] online game.\n\nHe returned to Origin in 2003 after two years of retirement, where he oversaw the development of ''[[Ultima X]]'', which was cancelled before release in 2004. Later, he served as president of Fastlane Games, Inc., working on the development of a massively multiplayer online game for [[NCsoft]] before retiring again in 2006.\n\n===Games===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Name\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Credited with\n! scope=\"col\" | Publisher\n|-\n| ''[[MiG Alley Ace]]'' || [[1983 in video gaming|1983]] || designer || [[MicroProse]]\n|-\n| ''[[Solo Flight (video game)|Solo Flight]]'' (Apple II port) || [[1983 in video gaming|1983]] || designer || MicroProse\n|-\n| ''[[Kennedy Approach]]'' || [[1985 in video gaming|1985]] || designer || MicroProse\n|-\n| ''[[Gunship (video game)|Gunship]]'' || [[1986 in video gaming|1986]] || director, designer, programmer || MicroProse\n|-\n| ''[[Sid Meier's Pirates!]]'' || [[1987 in video gaming|1987]] || artist || MicroProse\n|-\n| ''[[F-19 Stealth Fighter]]'' || [[1988 in video gaming|1988]] || programmer || MicroProse\n|-\n| ''[[F-15 Strike Eagle II]]'' || [[1989 in video gaming|1989]] || designer, programmer || MicroProse\n|-\n| ''[[Lightspeed (video game)|Lightspeed]]'' || [[1990 in video gaming|1990]] || designer, programmer || MicroProse\n|-\n| ''[[Hyperspeed (video game)|Hyperspeed]]'' || [[1991 in video gaming|1991]] || designer, programmer || MicroProse\n|-\n| ''[[F-117A Nighthawk Stealth Fighter 2.0]]'' || [[1991 in video gaming|1991]] || programmer || MicroProse\n|-\n| ''[[F-15 Strike Eagle III]]'' || [[1992 in video gaming|1992]] || producer, designer, programmer || MicroProse\n|-\n| ''[[Jane's AH-64D Longbow]]'' || [[1996 in video gaming|1996]] || producer || [[Electronic Arts]]\n|-\n| ''[[Jane's AH-64D Longbow|Jane's AH-64D Longbow \u2013 Flash Point: Korea]]'' || [[1996 in video gaming|1996]] || producer || Electronic Arts\n|-\n| ''[[Jane's Longbow 2]]'' || [[1997 in video gaming|1997]] || executive producer || Electronic Arts\n|-\n| ''[[Jane's F-15]]'' || [[1998 in video gaming|1998]] || executive producer || Electronic Arts\n|-\n| ''Fighter Pilot'' || [[1998 in video gaming|1998]] || executive producer || Electronic Arts\n|-\n| ''[[Sid Meier's Alpha Centauri]]'' || [[1999 in video gaming|1999]] || executive producer || Electronic Arts\n|}\n\n==Motorsports==\nHollis has won a total of thirteen [[SCCA]] Solo national championships, and is an instructor for the Evolution Performance Driving School. He served on the Solo Events Board (SEB) and its various advisory committees for 20 years, and is a very active member of the SCCA's Solo program. In 2006, his seven straight class wins and two Super Challenge victories lead to the Overall Championship in SCCA [[Autocross|ProSolo]].  In 2010, he repeated as Overall champ and added a Solo national championship in the STX class.  2011 brought another Solo championship, this time in STC.  2012 was another undefeated season in a new car and class (STF Mazda 2), with six straight Pro Solo class wins, a third Overall title and a fourth Solo championship.  Notably, Hollis has won the Pro Solo Super Challenge 14 times, 13 of which have been in the last ten years.  In 2014, he added an SMF class championship to his tally.\n\nContinuing through 2014, Hollis has been a participant in the [[One Lap of America]], finishing in the overall top ten for five years running. This, despite competing in a car from the slowest class. An avid track day enthusiast in the [http://www.OneLapCRX.com 